  "Question": "<p>I am struggling to understand the variable transformation of a Dirac delta function. More specifically, a transformation of the following type, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_816\"><math alttext=\"\\delta(a\\chi(z)-b)\\rightarrow\\delta(z-c)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>\u03b4</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>\u2192</mo><mrow><mi>\u03b4</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>z</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> Here, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_817\"><math alttext=\"a,b\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_818\"><math alttext=\"c\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>c</mi></semantics></math></span> are constants. The specific relationship between <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_819\"><math alttext=\"\\chi(z)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_820\"><math alttext=\"z\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>z</mi></semantics></math></span> is, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_821\"><math alttext=\"\\chi(z)=\\int{\\frac{1}{H(z)}dz}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u222b</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo rspace=\"0pt\">\ud835\udc51</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_822\"><math alttext=\"H(z)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is a non-zero, positive and smoothly varying function of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_823\"><math alttext=\"z\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>z</mi></semantics></math></span>. In the context of my Physics problem, for the sake of the interested audience, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_824\"><math alttext=\"H(z)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is the Hubble parameter of the Universe while <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_825\"><math alttext=\"\\chi(z)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> is the comoving distance and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_826\"><math alttext=\"z\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>z</mi></semantics></math></span> is the redshift of any time in the past.</p> <p><strong><em>So, let me add what I have done so far:</em></strong> </p> <p>I start by defining the Dirac delta function in the form a unit step function <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_827\"><math alttext=\"\\Theta(a\\chi(z)-b)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0398</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>as, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_828\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{d}{d(a\\chi(z))}\\Theta(a\\chi(z)-b)=\\delta(a\\chi(z)-b)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mfrac><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0398</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>\u03b4</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> Then converting this in the form of z using the chain rule as, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_829\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{d}{dz}\\Theta(a\\chi(z)-b)\\frac{dz}{d(a\\chi(z))}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0398</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span> Using the relation with <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_830\"><math alttext=\"H(z)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>, we can write the equation as, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_831\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{d}{dz}\\Theta(a\\chi(z)-b)\\frac{H(z)}{a}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0398</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mo>\u2062</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mi>a</mi></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span> Also, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_832\"><math alttext=\"\\chi(z)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>\u03c7</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> can also be replaced by the integral as well, so that left side containing the unit step function can be written as, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_833\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{H(z)}{a}\\frac{d}{dz}\\Theta(\\ a\\int_{0}^{z}{\\frac{1}{H(z^{\\prime})}dz^{% \\prime}}-b)\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mi>a</mi></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mfrac><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u0398</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mrow><mpadded lspace=\"5pt\" width=\"+5pt\"><mi>a</mi></mpadded><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u222b</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>z</mi></msubsup><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>z</mi><mo>\u2032</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo rspace=\"0pt\">\ud835\udc51</mo><msup><mi>z</mi><mo>\u2032</mo></msup></mrow></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>.</p> <p>After this, I am not sure what else to try. Hopefully, this addition helps. Also, please point out an error if you see one. </p>",
